1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:24,000
Are we rolling? Good morning. Good morning. It's December 6, 2015. I'm Emily Crosby and we're in Jackson, Mississippi with worth long.

3
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:37,000
And John Bishop is filming and we're here with the Civil Rights History Project which is co-sponsored by the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum on African American History and Culture.

4
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:41,000
Thanks for joining us this morning. Great to be here.

5
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:47,000
Could you tell us when and where you were born and about your family and community?

6
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:55,000
Right. I was born worth Westinghouse Long J.R.

7
00:00:55,000 --> 00:01:03,000
In Durham, North Carolina, born at Duke Hospital in January 15, 1936.

8
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:13,000
My mother Gertrude Watson Long, my father, Reverend William Worth Long.

9
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:32,000
We're both North Carolinians. My father, born over in New Charlotte in Mecklenburg County and my mother, born in Chatham County, which is basically from Durham about 30 miles.

10
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:49,000
And a center of where he as a presiding elder in the African Methodist Fiscal Zion Church had at least 10 churches.

11
00:01:50,000 --> 00:02:01,000
One of the things that he did was he was as a circuit rider was that he went from church to church.

12
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:13,000
He had what he called quarterly conferences. And at these conferences which he scheduled regularly, he would do the business of the church.

13
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:20,000
And the business of the church at that time was broad.

14
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:42,000
It included what they call general claims, you know, the financial aspects, the mortgages, the membership, foreign, I almost said foreign aid, but missionary funding, especially for Africa at that time.

15
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:53,000
And youth development, all of that within one church element.

16
00:02:53,000 --> 00:03:03,000
And my mother, complimented his work. Not as a secretary, but as an administrator.

17
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:29,000
As an administrator, she helped manage the financial aspects, not just of the home, but of his church, of this broad spectrum of network, with an African Methodist Fiscal Zion Church, AME Zion Church.

18
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:42,000
And I used to, she would sometimes talk about her early upbringing, as would he, but always in different settings.

19
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:50,000
My father would talk about it when he took me out to work me to death on the farm.

20
00:03:51,000 --> 00:04:04,000
And he would, if we were doing work that, that was close work, where we could talk, like he had a role and I had a role, then we could talk across the role.

21
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:19,000
But generally, he was behind the meal. We had a farm just five miles from Durham that was, that supplied us with milk.

22
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:24,000
And all about garden needs, garden food needs.

23
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:26,000
Ask me a couple questions.

24
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:33,000
Yeah. So, would you, if it's providing you milk, you have to go back and forth every day, or if people are helping with...

25
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:44,000
No, my father, for five days a week, got up in the morning, got into his jeep and drove out to the farm.

26
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:52,000
And stayed all day and came back at night. He came back in time for dinner. We waited for him in many cases.

27
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:57,000
And then we would eat our last meal.

28
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:13,000
But we're only talking about five miles away. On the weekends, one of his sons, in fact his own son, worth W, would get on his bicycle and pedal out with a hand.

29
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:22,000
With a milk hand and milk the cow. And feed the hogs, the two hogs, and feed the mule.

30
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:34,000
And then pedal with carefully, with the milk. In fact, I could almost turn the milk, depending on the roads that I drive home.

31
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:37,000
Come back and weather the road.

32
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:43,000
Right. But the milk had a five-night mile journey.

33
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:49,000
Did you enjoy it when you and your father would work so hard to talk?

34
00:05:49,000 --> 00:06:05,000
I did indeed. I liked it when he would not be formal. My father, as a preacher, had a formal aspect.

35
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:20,000
But he was a great storyteller and had a great sense of human. But when he got formal, I think he thought formal.

36
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:32,000
But his expressions were folk. He had folk expressions. He was what you know. He was known as a country preacher.

37
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:44,000
So he was what you call a shouting preacher, a shouting stomping preacher. And folk used to say in the African mode.

38
00:06:44,000 --> 00:07:01,000
And of course my father was a head the head the head the lineage, the African lineage in the sense that

39
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:13,000
he married his first wife, he married from Nigeria. They were free Africans.

40
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:30,000
As I looked through Cardiff G. Witton's book on free Negroes, what I recall, her family, her entire family, according to the census, were free.

41
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:48,000
But we cannot ascertain in our day off county North Carolina when they were freed. My father was almost adopted by that family when his folk in Mecklenburg County passed.

42
00:07:48,000 --> 00:08:05,000
And the family that had taken them in basically pledged their oldest daughter to him. Her name was Clara. But she died.

43
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:18,000
So then he married the second daughter, the second most biological daughter, Minnie. And so Minnie Banger, long, was her name.

44
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:47,000
And entering into that marriage, my father who then went to seminary in South Carolina took his wife and her mother as part of that marriage.

45
00:08:47,000 --> 00:09:06,000
And he went for a year as I understand it to hood theological seminary in South Carolina. And there's a school there called Livingston College. And in fact that was a school that I think he planned for me to go to.

46
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:13,000
But that's another story.

47
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:31,000
In going to his first church in Chatham County, North Carolina, Mitchell Chapel Church in Pittsburgh, North Carolina, when they arrived from Southbury,

48
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:58,000
it's my understanding that the church had provided a posse that had a dirt floor. And his wife shook her head, but her mother picked up a made a broom and started sweeping.

49
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:10,000
And at that time you could get straw grass and just wrap it, wrap it, made a broom and started sweeping. And that sealed a deal.

50
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:26,000
And he was on that district for over 30 years. He passed into the church for just a year or so and then became a full time for that in L.D. of the Durham district of the AME's I'm sure.

51
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:33,000
So both your parents, so eventually your father will be married.

52
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:53,000
My father, after the death of many his first wife, he married Gertrude Watson, who also, whose husband had died in a manning accident in Chatham County. And who had three daughters.

53
00:10:53,000 --> 00:11:22,000
My father by that time had two daughters. And so in this marriage, my mother, everybody called her Aunt Gertrude, my mother had gotten a settlement of a nice settlement for that time and was able to buy a house in Durham with a

54
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:49,000
duplex. And she rented out one side and they lived in the other. So she was considered doing pretty good, especially since both of them had gone as far as they could in school out in the country and got, I think, six grades. I think that was the maximum that you could get at that time.

55
00:11:49,000 --> 00:12:13,000
She had worked in Liget and Myers factory after the death of her husband as a cleaning up. But then she had worked for part of the Duke family as a cook and as a household domestic.

56
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:29,000
And she was very good at that because she entertained for my father when the bishop came or when dignitaries came, when people from the NAACB came and had a later time, Bishop Spots would.

57
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:48,000
I knew almost all of the officials within this African church. Right. Her brother, her stepbrother had been a bishop in that church and was assigned to the Liberia.

58
00:12:48,000 --> 00:13:03,000
The new new bishops went to the missions and when he came to Mount in Durham, he had a palmato.

59
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:23,000
That's what we call a palmato, but it was a palm, a gold palm attack clip. They had a box up. I mean a small box up. They would just go play the duplex. And I remember, he gave me one.

60
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:45,000
I couldn't believe it. And I stuck it in one of my best ties. Of course it ruined my tie because the thing was handmade. The point of it was, so I had this mixed feeling.

61
00:13:45,000 --> 00:14:09,000
Not about Africa or not about my uncle, but about the technology about the technology about this gift that cost me a tie. And I always remember that.

62
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:31,000
Bishop E.B. Watson was his name. Now other people visited us. In fact, I've been asking my family whether Ella Baker came through with the NAACP. There's a man about a name of Barnes who was with the NAACP. And we'll get to that.

63
00:14:31,000 --> 00:15:00,000
And that, of course, later, Alex Barnes, who headed the paper for the Amizan Church, it's called the... I can't do that right now. But Barnes came by with more than one person from the NAACP to sit at our Gertrude's table.

64
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:28,000
Which, right, Alex Barnes. And I heard many times. I heard them, you see, I was in the living room. I could hear them talking about different things. And they were talking about the business of the church in some cases. But mostly they were talking about the plate of Africans in the world.

65
00:15:28,000 --> 00:15:51,000
And about people in the plate of the pool in the world. So they separate. But what I'm trying to do here is to understand that they had a world consciousness. But they had also an African consciousness.

66
00:15:51,000 --> 00:16:14,000
They had some a root consciousness. That's what I'm talking about. And this is not in some political... This is a cultural religious aspect, I think. But it was deep down.

67
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:18,000
So both of your parents had country roots?

68
00:16:18,000 --> 00:16:26,000
Both came from rural backgrounds. They came to Durham.

69
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:44,000
Durham and the whole question of, there's a saying that you can take black folk from the country. But you can't take the country from black folk.

70
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:58,000
They said that proudly. Right, they said it a little different day. Right, but they said it.

71
00:16:58,000 --> 00:17:02,000
I'm trying to help you in that country. Bling things up.

72
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:12,000
So later, I would use that. I said, you can take the African from Africa. But you cannot take the African.

73
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:16,000
The African.

74
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:21,000
Right.

75
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:29,000
How did you talk about the difference between the country and Durham and how that interconnections and...

76
00:17:29,000 --> 00:17:47,000
And also as it relates to higher income, higher social status, we lived in a house that we inherited in a sense.

77
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:59,000
We had heard of the mortgage from my mother's sister, who's husband worked in Long Island in a assembly plan.

78
00:17:59,000 --> 00:18:09,000
And they had purchased this house in a place where they were going to build a college north-growing central university.

79
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:32,000
So people were building houses in that area. And it was on a place called Fomosa Street. Well, within a few months, people who were going to be at the college and who envisioned a different kind of community came in.

80
00:18:32,000 --> 00:18:42,000
And with architect, text, build their homes on what they renamed Fomosa Avenue.

81
00:18:42,000 --> 00:19:00,000
They were on Fomosa Avenue. And my house in the center was made of lumber. But these houses were brick and stone. Right.

82
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:16,000
This is not to tell the three little wolves. But on my left, not your Harris. He on an insurance company across the street, Mr. Henry McKinley-Machal.

83
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:32,000
And insurance company, the vice president of the college, Dr. A. L. the across the street from me, next to him, who first and then became president of North Fine Mutual Life and joined.

84
00:19:32,000 --> 00:20:00,000
The Chamberlain studio, music studio, a piano studio, where all the kids in the community from whatever background came in and learned how to play the piano from Mrs. Sharon, who was a daughter to CC Spall and who founded the North Fine Line of Mutual Life Insurance Company.

85
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:16,000
And an architect, a construction person in the next house, Mr. what doesn't matter. And the head of the bank in the next.

86
00:20:16,000 --> 00:20:30,000
This community, when I describe it, for instance, people say, oh, you, you, you went in a great community. Immediately.

87
00:20:30,000 --> 00:20:38,000
Now, this was the kind of community that I had to grow up in.

88
00:20:38,000 --> 00:20:48,000
How can I say some people move into a high-class neighborhood. But in your case, the high-class neighborhood came up.

89
00:20:48,000 --> 00:21:08,000
And we were not well-heated. You know, we didn't have a lot of resources at that time. And we, of course, everybody on that block sent their kids to not just private schools.

90
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:34,000
They sent them to Palmer Memorial Institute. At least for high school. Right. And some was when I was working out in the field. They sent them to camp at water. And Massachusetts. So they were a part of this, of, of, of, they were in a different world.

91
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:42,000
I, Durham was considered one of the, like, the financial center for Black America at that time.

92
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:54,000
At that time, right. And the most important element in their, in terms of education was not just the college. It was the business school.

93
00:21:54,000 --> 00:22:14,000
Started by a woman who realized that, that, that, that, in order to run a business, you had to have workers who, who were competent and who understood, you know, how to do accounting and how to do typing and correspondence.

94
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:40,000
And my sisters went to North Carolina College. But most of the employees for North Carolina Mutual went to the Durham Business School. And of course, she was a member of my father's church. So, I was going to be really, it doesn't have the same kind of income. You have the farm and you've got the church.

95
00:22:40,000 --> 00:22:51,000
And you don't have the same kind of education, although I have a world, the awareness and clearly skill. Right. So do you feel a part of this community? Do you feel a separation?

96
00:22:51,000 --> 00:23:05,000
I did at a certain point. I remember that my mother had a garden in the back. And she said she wanted me to come in and bring in a wagon load of manure from the farm.

97
00:23:05,000 --> 00:23:19,000
And I was trying to figure out how can I do that? I ended, and what should I do at late at night, early in the morning before the day? Because that was going to be embarrassing to me.

98
00:23:19,000 --> 00:23:37,000
So I took off early in the morning. I used to throw papers at 5.30 and get up at 5.30 and throw papers in the morning. But I rode my bicycle in the dock.

99
00:23:37,000 --> 00:23:44,000
I went out to the farm. The wagon was ready. You know, I hooked up the mule.

100
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:58,000
I drove speedily to the city line and on these paved streets, passed the college into Formosa, Avenue.

101
00:23:58,000 --> 00:24:19,000
And then I'm galloping and trying to get into my driveway. And the women come out, Mrs. Michelle and others come out on their porch and say, can we get somebody that fly all guy? Can we get somebody that fly all guy?

102
00:24:19,000 --> 00:24:36,000
It's like somebody had cell phones and told him what I was going to do. But then once that happened, I was valued in the community.

103
00:24:36,000 --> 00:24:43,000
I'm not going to say what you're saying.

104
00:24:43,000 --> 00:24:54,000
And we shared a, if we kill hogs, sometimes my father would come and put a hog on the back of a trailer behind his jeep and pull it into the bag.

105
00:24:54,000 --> 00:25:06,000
He would divide it up and package it and give it out in the community. He would share it in the community.

106
00:25:06,000 --> 00:25:23,000
I mean, the howl in the hall. We're talking about Tim LaLine. He didn't give them the hooves and the chidnets and the snout.

107
00:25:23,000 --> 00:25:44,000
I feel good in my community. I feel bad, but not just for that. People seem to like my work ethic. I took papers from the time I could carry the bag.

108
00:25:44,000 --> 00:25:48,000
I get up early in the morning and...

109
00:25:48,000 --> 00:25:56,000
So even though it's a kind of elite class, the community in the black world are good work ethic.

110
00:25:56,000 --> 00:26:08,000
Very valuable. And then at that time I had to collect also on the weekends. So I had an interaction with people in a way I never would have.

111
00:26:08,000 --> 00:26:20,000
And they would counsel me every time, every stop, a little lecture, a little piece of advice, you know.

112
00:26:20,000 --> 00:26:24,000
And then your money, not that.

113
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:28,000
It's supposed to be saying, you make it right.

114
00:26:28,000 --> 00:26:42,000
It's like a commercial. I said, I said, I mean, I listened to little tidbits of advice from people. But mostly good.

115
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:54,000
In fact, I use some papers in the school. Some of it folk. A little folk saying and stuff.

116
00:26:54,000 --> 00:27:00,000
But most of it having to do with success.

117
00:27:00,000 --> 00:27:12,000
If you work hard, the whole thing, if you put your nose to the ground and stone, if you...

118
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:20,000
You can make it. And that was the ethic.

119
00:27:20,000 --> 00:27:28,000
Very little interaction with anybody other than the black community.

120
00:27:28,000 --> 00:27:38,000
Because I lived on the edge of HATA, H-A-Y-T-I, HATA. And this community was self-sustaining.

121
00:27:38,000 --> 00:27:50,000
Two, you know, black-on theaters. The Bill Moore Drug Store.

122
00:27:50,000 --> 00:27:59,000
The hotel over the drug store. The theaters, the Riatto and the Book of Tea.

123
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:05,000
A service printing company. A printing company. I mean, in the same area.

124
00:28:05,000 --> 00:28:13,000
The reason I could catalog it in this way is that I took papers to everybody, you know, in that area.

125
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:19,000
So it's just like in my memory bank, is that entire community?

126
00:28:19,000 --> 00:28:29,000
Right. I can do it. Even though the doors are no longer there. They had opened. Are there?

127
00:28:29,000 --> 00:28:37,000
You mentioned different people from the church and the NAACP coming and sitting at the table and house.

128
00:28:37,000 --> 00:28:47,000
And your families and churches connections to Africa. And NAACP. And you said that the church, there was a lot of business of the church.

129
00:28:47,000 --> 00:28:49,000
Business of the church, yeah.

130
00:28:49,000 --> 00:28:57,000
So what are some of the things that your father and then your mother with them emphasized in terms of the church and the community?

131
00:28:57,000 --> 00:29:01,000
What were the things that they were trying to do? What was their vision?

132
00:29:01,000 --> 00:29:07,000
Well, we called it up, the, you know, community uplift.

133
00:29:07,000 --> 00:29:16,000
And they are saying, and they didn't just articulate it. They practiced it.

134
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:30,000
So, for instance, when young women who were required to live on campus, when the girls, so-called girls' dormitory got filled up.

135
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:40,000
And they had to live on campus or they had to live with a relative or someone certified.

136
00:29:40,000 --> 00:29:56,000
So, I grew up during, I can't remember the years, with as many as eight young women in my house.

137
00:29:56,000 --> 00:29:58,000
Between your sisters?

138
00:29:58,000 --> 00:30:02,000
For four, four, yes. And the college students.

139
00:30:02,000 --> 00:30:04,000
I must have been once. For my man.

140
00:30:04,000 --> 00:30:10,000
I was happy. I felt valued.

141
00:30:10,000 --> 00:30:14,000
In my community, in my household.

142
00:30:14,000 --> 00:30:22,000
Of course, again, the encouragement, but also the commercial and the lecture.

143
00:30:22,000 --> 00:30:34,000
Everybody always had something to say, but at the same time they had, they pointed you in a certain kind of direction.

144
00:30:34,000 --> 00:30:38,000
Did you do your homework?

145
00:30:38,000 --> 00:30:40,000
What did you do?

146
00:30:40,000 --> 00:30:46,000
Right. They tried you out in mathematics.

147
00:30:46,000 --> 00:30:55,000
My next, next to my next door neighbor was the German professor of languages, Doc Holmes.

148
00:30:55,000 --> 00:31:00,000
He would come back and he would speak German.

149
00:31:00,000 --> 00:31:06,000
And I would, I didn't know what the hell leaves. I said, why is he cussing me?

150
00:31:06,000 --> 00:31:10,000
And he would, he would just continue it.

151
00:31:10,000 --> 00:31:14,000
The next day he come back, he'd say something in French.

152
00:31:14,000 --> 00:31:24,000
And so finally, I said, well look, I'm a had, I'm a go up and ask this man, what are you trying to do?

153
00:31:24,000 --> 00:31:28,000
Right. So, it was about Christmas.

154
00:31:28,000 --> 00:31:39,000
And he came in, he said, he started singing, Oh, for a tree.

155
00:31:39,000 --> 00:31:41,000
In German.

156
00:31:41,000 --> 00:31:44,000
And I said, what are you doing?

157
00:31:44,000 --> 00:31:48,000
And he said, look, come on, let's sing.

158
00:31:48,000 --> 00:31:51,000
He said, I'm going on down to the house.

159
00:31:51,000 --> 00:31:53,000
And he said, well, let's sing.

160
00:31:53,000 --> 00:31:55,000
And then you can walk on back.

161
00:31:55,000 --> 00:32:05,000
And so I learned how to listen and and and pronounce.

162
00:32:05,000 --> 00:32:09,000
I learned some German on that occasion.

163
00:32:09,000 --> 00:32:19,000
But also I got a friend, Mr. Holmes was also in charge of the, the last exam program.

164
00:32:19,000 --> 00:32:24,000
So when Marion Anderson came to town, he had there enough seats.

165
00:32:24,000 --> 00:32:29,000
He would send me on up to the balcony and say, wait a minute, some seats in the balcony.

166
00:32:29,000 --> 00:32:47,000
And Paul Robison, I mean, some fantastic, a Philippa Scherler, a pianist, a young African American pianist.

167
00:32:47,000 --> 00:32:52,000
These are things that I actually miss myself.

168
00:32:52,000 --> 00:32:58,000
Over Northland Central, in the last exam program here.

169
00:32:58,000 --> 00:33:06,000
But the reason I started doing it was that he had first let me into the basketball games.

170
00:33:06,000 --> 00:33:08,000
And the football games.

171
00:33:08,000 --> 00:33:12,000
And then this dude was pretty smart.

172
00:33:12,000 --> 00:33:16,000
And then he let me go to the last exam.

173
00:33:16,000 --> 00:33:22,000
He told my mother, you know, it'd be good if he comes into to this program.

174
00:33:22,000 --> 00:33:35,000
So I saw all of the major classical talent of the day there at Northland Central.

175
00:33:35,000 --> 00:33:41,000
It opened a whole new realm to me.

176
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:52,000
I'm going to mess with your work.

177
