228
00:38:16,000 --> 00:38:24,000
And very often, you know, if I were not playing ball or doing whatever it was, I would go with him.

229
00:38:24,000 --> 00:38:32,000
But as a young man, as a young boy, when I went with him, he'd have to stop for gas.

230
00:38:32,000 --> 00:38:41,000
And he would...I remember in the wartime, he got special ration stamps because he was a minister.

231
00:38:41,000 --> 00:38:48,000
And because he was an evangelist minister, so that he had to go...

232
00:38:48,000 --> 00:38:54,000
He would stop and I remember being stopped at one place near Chapel Hill,

233
00:38:54,000 --> 00:38:58,000
but almost to Chatham County.

234
00:38:58,000 --> 00:39:03,000
And a young boy came out...

235
00:39:03,000 --> 00:39:08,000
The only son of this filling station.

236
00:39:08,000 --> 00:39:16,000
And he looked at my father and my father had on this hat with a three-piece suit,

237
00:39:16,000 --> 00:39:22,000
all black and a fairly decent looking car.

238
00:39:22,000 --> 00:39:26,000
And he looked at him and he didn't...

239
00:39:26,000 --> 00:39:30,000
I don't think he kind of figured what to call him.

240
00:39:30,000 --> 00:39:36,000
So then what you would do in that case is you could say, preach it.

241
00:39:36,000 --> 00:39:39,000
And you know.

242
00:39:39,000 --> 00:39:43,000
But you wouldn't say, sir.

243
00:39:43,000 --> 00:39:47,000
So he got it right.

244
00:39:47,000 --> 00:39:49,000
He said, preach it.

245
00:39:49,000 --> 00:39:53,000
I said, should I fill it up, preach it?

246
00:39:53,000 --> 00:39:55,000
He said, yes.

247
00:39:55,000 --> 00:40:01,000
And then my father continued to talk to him and build him up.

248
00:40:01,000 --> 00:40:11,000
And so finally, the kid washed his windshield.

249
00:40:11,000 --> 00:40:15,000
It's on the herd of...

250
00:40:15,000 --> 00:40:21,000
The kid washed his windshield and weighed.

251
00:40:21,000 --> 00:40:26,000
So I learned it may be two things.

252
00:40:26,000 --> 00:40:33,000
This is someone who had not had the black experience.

253
00:40:33,000 --> 00:40:34,000
Right.

254
00:40:34,000 --> 00:40:56,000
But he at least was able to build a human relationship at a peer level at that time,

255
00:40:56,000 --> 00:41:04,000
of that time, of a peer level at that time, at that level, at that time.

256
00:41:04,000 --> 00:41:06,000
And I learned from that.

257
00:41:06,000 --> 00:41:08,000
But it taught me two things.

258
00:41:08,000 --> 00:41:23,000
Because I tensed up when he was having trouble trying to decide how to address my father.

259
00:41:23,000 --> 00:41:31,000
But after a few times with different experiences and different styles,

260
00:41:31,000 --> 00:41:39,000
my father, people would sometimes say, sir, it's a little different.

261
00:41:39,000 --> 00:41:49,000
Because of his respect for him and of the respect that he had for himself.

262
00:41:49,000 --> 00:41:59,000
He had that courage.

263
00:41:59,000 --> 00:42:07,000
It taught me something about self-image, about how you see yourself, how others see you,

264
00:42:07,000 --> 00:42:13,000
and how you then you can see them in good light.

265
00:42:13,000 --> 00:42:19,000
But not through...

266
